---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Eclipse Science - Eclipse Central" description="Understand the astronomical science and physics behind solar and lunar eclipses.">
  <article class="page-content">
    <header class="page-header">
      <h1>The Science Behind Eclipses</h1>
      <p class="page-intro">Explore the fascinating astronomy and physics that create these celestial spectacles.</p>
    </header>

    <section class="science-section">
      <h2>üåç Celestial Mechanics</h2>
      <p>Eclipses occur due to the precise alignment of the Sun, Moon, and Earth. These alignments happen because all three bodies orbit in roughly the same plane, called the ecliptic.</p>
      
      <div class="mechanics-grid">
        <div class="mechanics-card">
          <h3>Solar Eclipse Formation</h3>
          <p>When the Moon passes directly between Earth and the Sun, it casts a shadow on Earth's surface. The Moon's shadow has two parts: the umbra (total shadow) and penumbra (partial shadow).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="mechanics-card">
          <h3>Lunar Eclipse Formation</h3>
          <p>When Earth passes between the Sun and Moon, Earth's shadow falls on the Moon. The Moon appears red during totality due to Earth's atmosphere bending and filtering sunlight.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="science-section">
      <h2>üî¢ The Mathematics</h2>
      
      <div class="math-facts">
        <div class="fact-card">
          <h3>Cosmic Coincidence</h3>
          <p>The Sun is ~400 times larger than the Moon, but also ~400 times farther away. This creates the "perfect" eclipse where the Moon can just cover the Sun's disk.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="fact-card">
          <h3>Shadow Speed</h3>
          <p>The Moon's shadow races across Earth at speeds of 1,500-5,000 mph (2,400-8,000 km/h), depending on your location relative to the eclipse path.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="fact-card">
          <h3>Saros Cycle</h3>
          <p>Eclipses repeat in cycles of approximately 18 years, 11 days, and 8 hours. This pattern is called the Saros cycle and was discovered by ancient astronomers.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="science-section">
      <h2>üî¨ Scientific Discoveries</h2>
      
      <div class="discovery-timeline">
        <div class="discovery-item">
          <h3>1919 - Einstein's Theory Confirmed</h3>
          <p>During a total solar eclipse, scientists observed starlight bending around the Sun, proving Einstein's theory of general relativity.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="discovery-item">
          <h3>1868 - Helium Discovery</h3>
          <p>The element helium was first discovered by studying the Sun's spectrum during a solar eclipse, 27 years before it was found on Earth.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="discovery-item">
          <h3>Ancient Predictions</h3>
          <p>Ancient civilizations learned to predict eclipses with remarkable accuracy using careful observations and mathematical patterns.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="science-section">
      <h2>üå°Ô∏è Physical Effects</h2>
      
      <div class="effects-grid">
        <div class="effect-card">
          <h3>Temperature Drop</h3>
          <p>During a solar eclipse, temperatures can drop 20¬∞F (11¬∞C) as the Moon blocks the Sun's heat.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="effect-card">
          <h3>Animal Behavior</h3>
          <p>Animals often exhibit unusual behavior during eclipses - birds may roost, crickets chirp, and flowers close.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="effect-card">
          <h3>Wind Changes</h3>
          <p>The rapid temperature change can alter local wind patterns and atmospheric conditions during totality.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="effect-card">
          <h3>Tidal Effects</h3>
          <p>While minimal, eclipses can slightly enhance tidal effects when the Sun, Moon, and Earth are perfectly aligned.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="future-science">
      <h2>üîÆ Future Eclipse Science</h2>
      <p>Scientists continue to use eclipses to study:</p>
      <ul class="science-list">
        <li><strong>Solar Corona:</strong> Understanding the Sun's outer atmosphere and solar wind</li>
        <li><strong>Exoplanet Detection:</strong> Using eclipse techniques to find planets around other stars</li>
        <li><strong>Atmospheric Research:</strong> Studying Earth's upper atmosphere during eclipses</li>
        <li><strong>Gravitational Studies:</strong> Testing theories about gravity and spacetime</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .page-content {
    max-width: 900px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: var(--space-8) 0;
  }

  .page-header {
    text-align: center;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-16);
  }

  .page-header h1 {
    font-size: var(--text-4xl);
    color: var(--color-primary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .page-intro {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
  }

  .science-section {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-16);
  }

  .science-section h2 {
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    color: var(--color-primary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-6);
  }

  .science-section > p {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .mechanics-grid,
  .effects-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr));
    gap: var(--space-6);
  }

  .mechanics-card,
  .effect-card {
    padding: var(--space-6);
    background: var(--color-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .mechanics-card h3,
  .effect-card h3 {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    color: var(--color-primary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .math-facts {
    display: grid;
    gap: var(--space-6);
  }

  .fact-card {
    padding: var(--space-6);
    background: var(--color-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .fact-card h3 {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    color: var(--color-primary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .discovery-timeline {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-6);
  }

  .discovery-item {
    padding: var(--space-6);
    background: var(--color-surface);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .discovery-item h3 {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--color-primary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .future-science {
    background: var(--color-surface);
    padding: var(--space-8);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .future-science h2 {
    font-size: var(--text-2xl);
    color: var(--color-primary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-6);
  }

  .future-science > p {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-6);
  }

  .science-list {
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
  }

  .science-list li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    color: var(--color-text);
  }

  .science-list strong {
    color: var(--color-primary);
  }

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .math-facts {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(300px, 1fr));
    }
  }
</style>